title: `$h_t_m_l::data()`
description: Generate HTML attributes from PHP array.
...

Attributes are generated from an array and will be renderred as `key="value"` in the output:

~~~ .php
echo HTML::span("", [
    'id' => 'color',
    'class' => 'color black',
    'style' => 'background-color:#000;',
    'data-key' => 'offset',
    'data-value' => 0
]);
~~~

Result:

~~~ .html
<span class="color black" id="color" style="background-color:#000;" data-key="offset" data-value="0"></span>
~~~

There are some special attributes which the value must be set as array:

~~~ .php
echo HTML::span("", [
    'class[]' => ['color', 'black'],
    'style[]' => [
        'background-color' => '#000'
    ],
    'data[]' => [
        'key' => 'offset',
        'value' => 0
    ]
]);
~~~

Result:

~~~ .html
<span class="color black" style="background-color:#000;" data-key="offset" data-value="0"></span>
~~~

Unlike the [`Union`][link:../union] class, `HTML` has its own attributes order:

 - `class`
 - `id`
 - `src`
 - `alt`
 - `width`
 - `height`
 - `property`
 - `name`
 - `content`
 - `href`
 - `rel`
 - `target`
 - `type`
 - `action`
 - `method`
 - `enctype`
 - `value`
 - `placeholder`
 - `label`
 - `selected`
 - `checked`
 - `disabled`
 - `readonly`
 - `style`